</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Transplantation is the surgical treatment of choice for end-stage organ failure. Transplantation procedures performed in the abdomen include liver, renal, pancreas, islet, intestinal, and multivisceral transplantations. Imaging plays a pivotal role in the posttransplantation setting for monitoring the transplant allograft and screening for complications. Knowledge of the surgical techniques employed in abdominal transplantation is essential because it facilitates radiologic understanding and interpretation of the posttransplantation anatomy. This article includes a basic description of the standard surgical techniques performed in the abdomen, with emphasis on the relevant vascular anastomotic reconstructions used. Posttransplantation complications can be broadly classified as vascular or nonvascular in origin. Many of these complications can be accurately depicted and characterized at imaging and dealt with definitively by using interventional radiology techniques, which can be graft- and life-saving and can obviate further complex surgical intervention. The article discusses imaging appearances of vascular complications and their consequences after transplantation in the abdomen. These vascular complications include arterial thrombosis, arterial stenosis, venous thrombosis and stenosis, arteriovenous fistula formation, and pseudoaneurysm formation. The relevant predisposing factors, clinical features, imaging appearances, and potential treatment options for vascular complications of various types of transplantation are presented in a logical and integrated fashion. Knowledge and imaging recognition of the posttransplantation vascular complications discussed in this article will aid radiologists in accurate imaging characterization and thereby facilitate appropriate clinical management and therapy.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2013</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.333125728">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.333125728">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig01.jpeg" height="958" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Schematic of an orthotopic liver transplant shows the location of vascular and biliary anastomoses.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig02.jpeg" height="991" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Schematic of a renal transplant shows the location of vascular and urologic anastomoses.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig03a.jpeg" height="875" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig03a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig03b.jpeg" height="828" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig03b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig04a.jpeg" height="1098" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig04b.jpeg" height="1135" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig05.jpeg" height="1025" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig05" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Schematic of a small intestine transplant. The donor SMA may be anastomosed to the recipient aorta (as shown here) or to the recipient SMA. The donor SMV may be anastomosed to the recipient portal vein, SMV, or IVC (as shown here).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig05">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig06.jpeg" height="1280" width="940" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Multivisceral transplantation of liver, pancreas, stomach, and small bowel in a 20-month-old boy with intestinal atresia, liver failure due to total parenteral nutrition, and mesenteric venous thrombosis. Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows the liver, pancreas, stomach, and small bowel transplants <i>(Tx)</i>. A gastrostomy tube is present with the cuff inflated within the gastric lumen (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig07a.jpeg" height="1131" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig07a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig07b.jpeg" height="1137" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig07b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig08.jpeg" height="1280" width="903" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Nonanastomotic ductal stricture with associated bile leak in a 24-year-old male liver transplant recipient with underlying ABO incompatibility. Image obtained at endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography shows a high-grade stricture of the proximal common duct (arrow). Contrast medium extravasation (*) due to an ntrahepatic bile leak is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig09.jpeg" height="1088" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Multifocal infected bilomas or biliary abscesses and common duct stricture due to underlying hepatic artery thrombosis in a 60-year-old male liver transplant recipient. Maximum intensity projection image from MR cholangiopancreatography shows several intrahepatic cystic collections (*) that communicate with the biliary tree, findings that represent infected bilomas or biliary abscesses. In addition, the distal common duct (arrow) is stenosed and shows irregular luminal narrowing. Treatment typically requires hepatic retransplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig10.jpeg" height="853" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Focal infarct in a 51-year-old female renal transplant recipient. Sagittal color Doppler US image shows a hypoechoic wedge-shaped region (arrow) void of color Doppler flow, a finding that represents a focal infarct in the renal transplant. Over time, infarction will lead to atrophy, and a cortical scar will appear.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig11.jpeg" height="1280" width="914" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> A distal ureteric stricture in a 53-year-old female renal transplant recipient. Coronal image from transplant <i>(Tx)</i> nephrostography shows a high-grade stricture (arrow) of the distal ureter with an associated absence of contrast medium passage into the bladder, a finding indicative of complete urinary tract obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig12a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1255" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig12b.jpeg" height="1051" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig12c.jpeg" height="798" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig12d.jpeg" height="798" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig13a.jpeg" height="944" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig13b.jpeg" height="994" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig13c.jpeg" height="1186" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig14a.jpeg" height="980" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig14b.jpeg" height="998" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig14c.jpeg" height="1014" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig15.jpeg" height="1011" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Partial thrombosis of the IVC below the level of the left hepatic vein <i>(LHV)</i> in a 6-year-old left-lobe liver transplant <i>(Tx)</i> recipient. Sagittal color Doppler US image of the transplant shows an echogenic thrombus in the IVC below the level of the hepatic venous confluence.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig16a.jpeg" height="1036" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig16b.jpeg" height="1078" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig16c.jpeg" height="1062" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig16d.jpeg" height="1018" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig17a.jpeg" height="904" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig17b.jpeg" height="1085" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig18.jpeg" height="855" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Segmental portal vein thrombosis in a 48-year-old female islet transplant recipient. Sagittal (left) and axial (right) gray-scale US images of the liver show a nonocclusive thrombus (arrows) in the anterior branch of the right portal vein. The main, right posterior, and left portal vein branches remained patent. There were no clinical sequelae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig19a.jpeg" height="1015" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig19b.jpeg" height="1005" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig19c.jpeg" height="1185" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig19d.jpeg" height="1174" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig19d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig20a.jpeg" height="1010" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig20b.jpeg" height="1059" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig20c.jpeg" height="1174" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.333125728/asset/images/125728fig21.jpeg" height="799" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Iatrogenically induced hepatic pseudoaneurysm following islet transplantation in a 54-year-old male patient. Transverse magnified color Doppler (left) and spectral Doppler (right) US images of the right lobe of the liver show a small ovoid pseudoaneurysm (arrow) that has disorganized flow (mixture of red and blue at color Doppler US) and a weak arterialized waveform pattern (at spectral Doppler US).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.333125728&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Organ Procurement and Transplantation Network. <a href="https://optn.transplant.hrsa.gov/latestData/step2.asp">http://optn.transplant.hrsa.gov/latestData/step2.asp</a>. Accessed February 17, 2012.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https: